    label: 'Mission, Vision, Goals, and Core Values', references: [ETS, PSEL, CONTINUOUS_IMPROVEMENT],
    questions: [
      q('What should precede revision of a school mission?', 'A new leader wants to replace the mission during the first week. What is the strongest first move?', 'Analyze disaggregated student, opportunity, implementation, climate, and stakeholder evidence before facilitating an inclusive review.', ['Copy a highly rated school mission.', 'Ask only the leadership team to draft it privately.', 'Delay all review until test scores rise.'], 'A mission should respond to the actual school context and each student, so leaders first establish a representative evidence base and an inclusive process.'),
      q('What makes a school vision educationally useful?', 'A vision statement is inspiring but has no implications for practice. What revision is needed?', 'Connect a clear future state for every student with shared values, observable commitments, and decisions the community can enact.', ['Add more slogans without defining action.', 'Limit the vision to the highest-performing group.', 'Replace the vision with an annual event calendar.'], 'A useful vision guides choices and collective action; it expresses an equitable future, shared commitments, and a basis for monitoring progress.'),
      q('Which goal is best designed for strategic monitoring?', 'A team proposes that students will improve soon. How should the leader strengthen the goal?', 'Specify the learner outcome, baseline, target, timeframe, relevant subgroup evidence, responsible actions, and review intervals.', ['Use a broad aspiration with no measure.', 'Set a target without examining baseline variation.', 'Measure only staff attendance at meetings.'], 'A strategic goal is measurable and time bound while linking outcomes to adult actions, access, implementation, and scheduled evidence reviews.'),
      q('How should district and school goals relate?', 'A school priority conflicts with a district requirement. What should the leader do?', 'Clarify the governing requirements, align the school strategy where possible, and document any needed escalation or approved adaptation.', ['Ignore the district requirement.', 'Abandon all school-specific needs.', 'Let each teacher choose whether policy applies.'], 'Strategic coherence requires lawful alignment with district direction while preserving evidence-based responses to the school context through authorized processes.'),
      q('What is the role of core values in leadership?', 'A leader invokes equity only in speeches. What would demonstrate that it is a core value?', 'Use the value consistently in resource, access, staffing, instruction, discipline, communication, and improvement decisions.', ['Display the value on posters only.', 'Apply it only when no tradeoff is required.', 'Treat values as private preferences.'], 'Core values become credible when they shape routine and difficult decisions, are made visible in practice, and are open to evidence and accountability.'),
      q('How should leaders engage dissent during goal setting?', 'Several families question a proposed attendance goal. What response best supports shared commitment?', 'Surface the concerns, examine evidence and barriers with affected groups, revise the strategy when warranted, and explain the final rationale.', ['Label disagreement as resistance.', 'Hold the vote before sharing the data.', 'Remove dissenting families from the process.'], 'Inclusive strategic leadership treats dissent as information, protects meaningful participation, and builds commitment through transparent evidence and reasoning.'),
      q('What is a sound way to prioritize among several needs?', 'A needs assessment identifies ten urgent problems. How should the team choose a focus?', 'Apply transparent criteria such as impact, inequity, urgency, evidence, feasibility, dependencies, and alignment with mission.', ['Select the easiest problem automatically.', 'Choose the concern raised by the loudest person.', 'Pursue all ten with equal resources.'], 'Explicit criteria make tradeoffs visible and reduce arbitrary priority setting while keeping student impact and equity central.'),
      q('How should a leader communicate strategic goals?', 'Staff members can repeat a goal but cannot explain their role. What is missing?', 'Translate the goal for different audiences into responsibilities, supports, evidence, timelines, and feedback channels while preserving one coherent message.', ['Send the same dense memo repeatedly.', 'Limit information to administrators.', 'Change the goal for each audience.'], 'Communication supports implementation when stakeholders understand the purpose, their contribution, available support, and how progress will be discussed.'),
      q('When should a strategic goal be revised?', 'A goal is off track after two review cycles. What is the best leadership response?', 'Examine implementation and outcome evidence, test the causal assumptions, consult affected stakeholders, and document a justified adaptation.', ['Lower the target without analysis.', 'Keep every action unchanged to show resolve.', 'Replace the team before reviewing conditions.'], 'Responsible adaptation distinguishes weak implementation from a weak theory of action and changes the plan transparently rather than reacting to one number.'),
    ],
