    questions: [
      q('What makes a personnel selection process defensible?', 'A hiring team wants to choose a familiar candidate before interviews. What should the leader require?', 'Use job-related criteria, structured evidence, trained diverse reviewers, consistent procedures, reference checks, documented reasoning, accessibility, and current employment requirements.', ['Use personal familiarity as the main criterion.', 'Ask different protected-status questions of each candidate.', 'Discard interview records immediately.'], 'A fair selection system links evidence to role requirements and applies transparent, consistent, lawful procedures that reduce arbitrary influence.'),
      q('How should an employee performance concern be addressed?', 'A supervisor has repeated concerns but has provided no specific feedback. What should happen?', 'Document job-related evidence, clarify expectations, hear the employee response, provide support and timelines, monitor progress, and follow current contract, policy, and due process.', ['Build a secret case until dismissal.', 'Discuss the employee publicly.', 'Use student rumors as the sole evidence.'], 'Effective supervision is timely, evidence based, developmental, documented, and procedurally fair; exact requirements vary by jurisdiction and agreement.'),
      q('What is the foundation of a high-quality emergency operations plan?', 'A school emergency plan was copied from another campus and has never been exercised. What should leaders do?', 'Develop a collaborative, site-specific emergency operations plan that defines risk, roles, communication, access, reunification, training, exercises, evidence-based revision, and recovery.', ['Rely on the copied plan without review.', 'Keep roles unknown to avoid alarm.', 'Plan only for the initial response.'], 'Federal guidance describes comprehensive, collaborative, regularly reviewed EOPs supported by training, exercises, accessible procedures, and recovery planning.'),
      q('How should leaders communicate during an active emergency?', 'Unverified information is spreading during an incident. What is the best leadership approach?', 'Follow the incident communication plan, coordinate with authorized responders, prioritize life safety, share verified accessible updates, protect sensitive details, and document decisions.', ['Post speculation immediately.', 'Use several conflicting unofficial channels.', 'Delay all communication until the incident ends.'], 'Crisis communication must be timely, coordinated, accurate, accessible, and bounded by safety, privacy, and operational needs.'),
      q('What belongs in continuity planning?', 'A cyber incident makes core systems unavailable for several days. What should the school have prepared?', 'Prioritized essential functions, offline contacts and procedures, tested backups, alternative instructional and operational workflows, decision authority, communications, restoration criteria, and after-action review.', ['A single online copy of the plan.', 'Dependence on one unavailable employee.', 'Restoration without checking integrity.'], 'Continuity planning identifies essential services and rehearsed alternatives so learning, safety, communication, and recovery can continue through disruption.'),
      q('How should after-action review be conducted?', 'A drill exposes delayed assistance for students needing mobility supports. What is the correct response?', 'Document the gap without blame, involve affected participants and qualified personnel, assign corrective actions and owners, revise the plan, retrain, and exercise the change.', ['Remove the finding from the report.', 'Repeat the identical drill without changes.', 'Assume individuals will improvise next time.'], 'Exercises create value when leaders convert evidence into accessible corrective action, accountability, retraining, and a new test of the system.'),
    ],
